Why America Should Not Reelect President Bush
I have never particularly engaged myself politically, but these are not normal times.
President George W. Bush endangers the security of the United States and the world and simultaneously undermines American values.
Because of my opposition to him, I have been demonized by Bush's campaign team.
President Bush ran in 2000 with a campaign promise of a foreign policy of "humility."
If he is re-elected, this will be a vote for the Bush doctrine of preemptive war - and the invasion of Iraq - and the world will have to live with the consequences.
By rejecting Bush's policy at the ballot boxes, America has a chance to regain the respect and support of the world.
The terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001 required a strong response.
They have, however, also led to the suspension of the critical process so indispensable to democracy - the comprehensive and honest discussion of pending issues.
Bush silenced criticism by labeling it unpatriotic.
For the duration of 18 months following September 11, he has succeeded in suppressing any dissent.
In this way, he has led America in the wrong direction.
In fact, Bush played directly into Osama bin Laden's hands.
The invasion of Afghanistan - where bin Laden lived and Al Qaeda maintained their training camps - was justified.
The invasion of Iraq was not.
He was Bush's unintentional gift to bin Laden.
Immediately following September 11, spontaneous expressions of sympathy for America emerged all over the world.
These have given way to widespread resentment.
Clearly more people than on September 11 are now willing to risk their lives to kill Americans.
Bush likes to claim that terrorists hate Americans for what they are - a freedom-loving people - and not for what they do.
War and occupation, however, produce innocent victims.
We Americans count our fallen soldiers - more than 1,000 in Iraq.
The rest of the world also counts the Iraqis killed every day - perhaps twenty times as many.
Similarly, the torture of prisoners in the Abu Ghraib prison was not the work of a few "bad apples".
It was part of a system established by Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld for dealing with prisoners.
The world public condemns America, and our troops in Iraq are paying the price for it.
Bush has convinced people that America's security is in good hands by addressing the fears caused by the attacks of September 11th.
In times of danger people gather around their flag, and Bush has exploited this by fostering a sense of threat.
His campaign assumes that people are ultimately not interested in the truth and almost believe anything if it is repeated often enough.
Something must be wrong with America if we fall for it.
For example, still about 40% of all Americans believe that Saddam Hussein had something to do with September 11th, although the September 11th Inquiry Commission - set up by Bush and chaired by a Republican - clearly determined that no such connection existed.
You want to scream: "Wake up, America.
Don't you realize that we are being led by the nose?"
The war in Iraq was based from the beginning until the end on false assumptions - if it ever finds an end.
It was a war of one's own decision, not out of necessity.
Moreover, America entered the war under an excuse: mass destruction weapons could not be found, and the connection to Al Qaeda cannot be proven.
Bush then claimed that America had entered the war to liberate Iraq.
But you cannot impose democracy on anyone by force.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and the Iraqis - and the world - can be glad to be rid of him.
However, America had the duty to ensure justice and order; instead, we passively watched as Baghdad and other cities were looted.
If we had really been concerned about the Iraqi people, we would have had to deploy a larger number of soldiers for the occupation.
We would not only have had to protect the Ministry of Oil, but also other ministries, museums, and hospitals.
Worse still: Where American soldiers encountered resistance, they used methods - such as breaking into private homes and mistreating prisoners - that shocked and humiliated the population and thus provoked bitterness and anger.
The retreats and missteps of the Bush administration are legion.
First, the Iraqi army was disbanded, then America tried to restore it.
First, the USA tried to eliminate the Baathists, then America sought their help.
When the uprisings became too difficult to handle, America installed an Iraqi government.
The man chosen as their leader was a protégé of the CIA with the reputation of a "strong man" - anything but a democratic decision.
Despite the efforts of Bush's campaign team to spin the situation, the situation in Iraq is bleak.
A large part of the western part of the country was left to the insurgents. The prospects for holding free and fair elections in January are rapidly fading.
Civil war threatens.
Bush's war in Iraq has also caused immense damage to America, weakened its military striking power, and undermined the morale of the troops.
Before the war, America could project an image of overwhelming strength.
No longer today.
Afghanistan is slipping out of control.
North Korea, Iran, Pakistan, and other countries are pursuing nuclear programs with renewed vigor.
One can criticize the Bush administration on many other political issues, but none is as significant as Iraq.
The cost of the war so far amounts to nearly 200 billion dollars and will continue to rise, because the invasion of Iraq was much easier than the withdrawal will be.
Bush has goaded John Kerry to explain what he would do differently.
Kerry responded that he would have done everything differently and that he would be in a better position to free us from our entanglement.
But this will not be easy for him either, because America is stuck in a swamp.
Leading military experts and diplomats have desperately warned Bush not to march into Iraq.
He ignored them.
He suppressed the critical process with the argument that any criticism of the commander-in-chief would endanger US troops.
But this is Bush's war, and he should be held accountable for it.
The Americans should pause for a moment and ask themselves: To whom do we owe this mess?
A moment of reflection would presumably raise another question: Does Bush's cowboy behavior qualify him to remain America's supreme commander?
